{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "They are subject to the most extensive DSA obligations, including external risk auditing under Article 28, data access provisions under Article 31, heightened due diligence duties under Article 27, additional transparency requirements under Article 24, and potential blacklisting under Article 27 in case of systematic non-compliance.This graduated approach reflects the consensus that regulatory burdens should be calibrated to intermediaries' capacity and risk-influencing role, following the principle of proportionality.",
    "Indeed, one of the DSA's core objectives is to balance the power structures in the digital economy, limiting the democracy-threatening power of private companies (while not entering the realm of competition law).",
    "It aims to strike a balance between imposing adequate responsibilities on influential entities while not stifling innovation through excessive burdens on small players.",
    "To address these inherent tensions, the regulation adopts an asymmetrical approach, which has previously been adopted in EU legislation, such as in the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) [45].",
    "To effectively enforce these asymmetrical obligations, it is crucial to categorize intermediaries within the DSA framework."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "To address these inherent tensions, the regulation adopts an asymmetrical approach, which has previously been adopted in EU legislation, such as in the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) [45]."
  ]
